Many of those statements are solidly corroborated Daetien.  We know for certain that sworn statement of the prisoner made to stand on a box and hooked up to wires is telling the truth.  Or is that photo a lie?  Also, the first of the statements I quote, the detainee whose broken leg was repeatedly beaten until he was made to say he loved Jesus and to deny his religion- that was corroborated at the trial of Spc. Jeremy Sivits who turned state's evidence and cooperated for a light sentence.  <br>
<br>
Many of the attorneys for the accused have similarly corroborated these statements- the only one not corroborated is from the un-named detainees, none of whose statements I cited.  The defence teams for the accused are NOT basing their defence on the idea that the statements are false or that the detainees are lying.  They are basing it on the argument of shared responsibility, that their clients were ordered to do it, that the abuse was stated policy and that there is no accountability higher up.  Given their open and free access to the facts and US military personnel witnesses, I think that is *more* than enough corroboration.  Again, you don't have to believe me: the attorneys, the soldiers who were there and have corroborated it, their statements openly submitted to the defence attorneys- you are free to believe all of them are lies Daetien.  That is your right.  <br>
<br>
But I'm confident that the majority of this abuse did happen as stated by the detainees and as reported by the Washington Post, as confident as I was in my prediction before the war (extensively posted and argued on this very forum) that WMDs wouldn't be found and that Iraq was no significant threat- and the significant terrorist whirlwind we would all reap as a result of invading a sovreign nation.  I have since been proven right on all those counts, and am confident the same will happen again- the trials of the accused are coming up and we'll both be there to see the truth that I am sure will emerge.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>&quot;sworn satements' mean exactly jack shit to me when made by poeple who hate us.. i can give sworn statements about someone i have an agenda against until i'm blue in the face and that doesn't make them true.. <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
Did you even read my post or the statements?  Mohanded Juma Juma, the Shia tribal chieftan who risked his life repeatedly and the lives of his tribesmen during the conflict.  What possible hatred could he have for the coalition that he would willingly risk Saddam's secret police, Amn-al-Khas, Mukhabarat and Fedayeen to bring out vital intelligence to the Basra attack?  What anti-US agenda did he have?  The street vendor who sold food and praised the invasion for resurrecting his business in Baghdad, and used to work for the CPA- how is it he hates America exactly?  And more to the point, without any measure of due process, how did he or anyone else in that shithole of a prison deserve any of what happened to them?<br>
<br>
You also seem to be saying that <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>every single detainee</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> whether civilian, militant or insurgent hates the United States.  What analysis are you basing this on may I ask? After all, polls show Iraqi Sunni civilians marginally support the war, so a representative sample of civvies picked up in random residential sweeps should also have at least half of a supportive base.  In fact, the majority of the civilians interviewed were indifferent towards America before torture, and most of the insurgents don't hate the US, they just love their country.  US soldiers don't hate Iraqis, but they believe in their mission- why can't you believe the same is true of insurgents btw?  <br>
<br>
Your statement has an edge of bitter truth in one sense however- although many of the prisoners didn't hate the US before they were tortured, a lot of them are likely to now.  What's more, the popular support for the secular insurgents will almost certainly increase.  Not to mention that the size of the sea that terrorists freely swim in just got a whole lot bigger.  It seriously threatens the overall mission any way you look at it.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>All those &quot;sworn statements&quot; were made by people who must have been placed into custody for a reason. I am not saying they were definitely guilty or innocent but someone arrested them for a reason.<br>
<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
If that's what you believe, but what about this statement you made:<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Innocent until PROVEN guilty...<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
Let me get this straight- you have no problem with justifying the detention of civilians in random sweeps- but you have a problem with prejudging the conduct of US soldiers?  Sounds like a bit of a dichotomy to me.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>If I was a terrorist thats just what I would do since what is the difference? I am already in jail and if I am guilty am probably going to stay there.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
Woah there pardnuh...you just said innocent until proven guilty- but the tone of this statement sounds like you disagree with the US appointed CPA.  Who said that 70-80% of the inmates were civilians picked up in random sweeps from residential areas.  That's taking the CPA estimate at face value of course, they have every interest in maximizing the list of potential suspects.    <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>For example, if I know that detainee #1 knows info about a terrorist attack that will quite likely take friendly lives through unconventional means or will kill/injure noncombatants then I will be the first one to wire his balls to a car battery. It's that plain and simple...<br>
<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
So you approve of extreme or brutal treatment of defenceless people if it might save lives Brotherscale?  Leaving aside the obvious question of how you're sure if someone is witholding such information- it removes a LOT of the moral barriers that seperate us from terrorists.  Some of those tortured might know something, but many won't- that is the nature of random sweeps.  You are essentially employing collective punishment for possible information- something the Nazis did extensively, as well as the worst of the brutal police states.  Idi Amin and Stalin would wring their hands with glee at the very thought.  Killing or maiming civilians in the name of saving life is just about the most repugnant thing to me, I would hope it was to most people.<br>
<br>
Not to mention that it's counter-productive.  Out of the 20% of non-civilian detainees, more than half are criminals.  The remaining 10% are the high-value targets.  The collective torture and punishment of the civilian majority alongside Ba'athists and terrorists is likely to create hatred for the occupation where none previously existed.  Any talk of the torture &quot;saving lives&quot; is pretty much bullshit if you consider that the result of the scandal will likely kill many more American/coalition soldiers than any possible benefit from torturing them.  You can't forget Brotherscale that the only way the mission succeeds is to dry up support for the insurgency while increasing public support for the short-term occupation.  Both have been dealt a serious, possibly a crippling blow by Abu Ghraib- a few less operational casualties isn't worth the price, either morally or practically.<br>
<br>
Another thing.  Suppose we consider that the motivation for the murder and dragging of the 4 contractors was designed to provoke a US withdrawal from Fallujiah?  Local Sunni militias and leaders would certainly view a withdrawal as a key part of saving lives and avoid the collective punishment of civilians.  By the same sort of reasoning you use, if brutal treatment saves the lives of their militia and civilians then that barbaric behavior is justified in achieving a broader goal.  In fact, their goal *was* achieved- US troops withdrew from Fallujiah.  Whether or not they are linked will be as irrelevant to the militias as the torture of civilians seems irrelevant to you.  <br>
<br>
Let's make it clear- there is no moral equivalence between the two acts, I make the comparison purely for strategic purposes- since Brotherscale used the argument in favor of torture for &quot;strategic benefit&quot;.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Everybody in San Quentin is innocent btw.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
Convicted in a court of law and picked up off the street- there's a world of difference there.  Saying there isn't is simply a denial of a key principle that makes us a civilized society.  <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Nobody seems to show pictures of the 4 civilian contractors that a huge crowd tore to pieces and dragged through the streets.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
The angry mob doesn't claim to represent democracy and free society values or believe in the military imposition of those values- the United States <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>does</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> and never ceases to remind other nations to clean up their act.  It doesn't mean the slaughter of the four contractors was justified or civilized but neither the mob or the Iraqi people at large hold themselves or others to the same standard by force... as the US has been doing.<br>
<br>
Remember that the United States is occupying another country- and is therefore responsible for security, infrastructure and all the bells &amp; whistles of an occupying power.  Whether you think the abuses were right or wrong, big or small, they were criminal.  Under the UCMJ, Geneva Conventions, Universal Treatment of POWs Treaty, just about every legislative rule on the subject, it is illegal.  On a somewhat related note cus, remember that conversation you and I had about Guantanomo Bay a couple months ago?  I argued that it would increase tolerance for barbaric Stalinist behavior under a veneer of moral justification.  <br>
<br>
I argued that saying &quot;a little evil behavior is OK in defeating *potential* agents of a greater evil&quot;---- would eventually lead to the thought &quot;well perhaps a moderate evil is OK....&quot;  I think the responses on this thread to the abuses is a measure of proof that the denial of due process at Guantanomo is leading to greater tolerance for brutality in other related areas.  I'm <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>genuinely worried</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> that we'll all wake up one day and find that we're a lot closer to the enemy in moral terms than we've ever been in recent history.<br>
<br>
The reason it's such a big deal cus is that without WMDs or a real security threat to the West, the only remaining justification is the moral justification for removing a tyrant.  That justification is considerably lessened by using Saddam's favorite mini-Gulag to continue a slightly less brutal version of the same torture of civilians picked up in random sweeps.  Whether or not one supports the torture of civilians arrested I think it's hard to argue that it won't have a serious effect on the success or failure of the Iraq policy.  If that weren't the case then why were huge numbers of these supposed &quot;evil America-hating terrorists&quot; released after the scandal?  It certainly isn't appeasement- the Bush administration doesn't believe in appeasement.  Historians will look back on this as immoral- probably, as another in the series of policy failure blunders- <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>without a doubt</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->.<br>
