That's the report Gen. A. Taguba wrote which categorically confirms almost all of the abuses and in which Brig. Karpinski was castigated for letting it happen on her watch.  That's mainly why I was so suprised by your response, that you haven't read the statements explains why you wrote it.  If you'd read the statements I doubt you'd have said what you did.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>i do however believe the worldwide media, including that of the u.s., is always ready to jump on and magnify and exploit every little screwup by the u.s.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
A small correction if I may- replace every &quot;u.s.&quot; in your quote with &quot;GW Bush administration&quot; and you're absolutely right.  I can't stress this point enough- Bush Sr., Reagan, Clinton were all rapturously received for the most part when they went abroad by both foreign publics and media, because they by and large acted even-handedly and tried to build consensus rather than throwing it away.  <br>
<br>
After 9/11 the world was united in standing with the United States in sorrow and resolve, in an unprecedented diplomatic alliance against terrorism.  History will be astonished at the speed and callousness with which that alliance was sundered by belligerence from the Bush administration.  The entire world is far less safe because of that and the Iraq war, terrorism has never been so attractive to the mainstream because of it.<br>
<br>
Also, this administration is the most unilateral US administration in the post Bretton-Woods era, more than 50 years.  There are a series of incredibly offensive foreign policies that have alienated the international community.<br>
<br>
Most notable are:  <br>
<br>
-Refusing to support the Kyoto protocols on the environment<br>
<br>
-Ignoring the Earth summit on the environment<br>
<br>
-Siding with China in the trial-free detention of political prisoners, the first time a US administration has endorsed such behavior<br>
<br>
-Withdrawing from the ABM treaty<br>
<br>
-Refusing to sign a universal agreement banning land-mines designed to maim rather than kill<br>
<br>
-Pre-emptive war doctrine, throwing away all of the post WWII rules of diplomatic engagement regarding conflict<br>
<br>
-Refusal to ratify the International Criminal Court (ICC) for war-crimes trials.<br>
<br>
-Rushing to war in Iraq on a security pretext:  people have I believe forgotten how quickly the administration pushed for war at all costs<br>
<br>
-Abandoning the traditional role of the US as an even-handed negotiator in the Middle East peace process.  A <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/americas/3681999.stm" target="top">letter</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--> was recently written to the President by about 50 former US diplomats and foreign intelligence officers making this very point.  This is the first time so many former foreign service officials have protested so widely over the Middle East policy issue.<br>
<br>
-The unbidded exclusive awards of contracts to US corporations to rebuild Iraq, particularly Bechtel and Haliburton that have well publicized links to key members of the Bush cabinet.  This creates the impression of war profiteering.<br>
<br>
-Guantanomo Bay.  Citizens from several countries, and three children (aged 9-14) being detained without trial is terribly worrying to all the United States' traditional allies.  The only nations that have taken great heart from Guantanomo are autocratic regimes that know the US can now no longer criticize them for their abysmal human rights records.  Innocent until proven guilty no longer seems to apply, the Geneva convention specifically forbids indefinite detention of this kind under any circumstance.  Many feel Abu Ghraib and Guantanomo are two sides of the same coin.<br>
<br>
Those are a few of the key reasons that while Reagan, Bush Sr. and Clinton were rapturously greeted as leaders of the free world, GW Bush has tens of thousands of protestors following his every visit.  This isn't the way people have always felt about the US.  Prior to the Bush administration the only way you could have got 100,000 protestors marching in London was when the Chinese president or some other autocratic dictator visited.  President Bush is the first US president in the history of the United States to be greeted by such large-scale protests in nearly every country he visits.  <br>
<br>
So while I agree that the Bush administration is routinely and roundly criticized by global publics, pundits and the media- I also agree that it is with good reason.  There are serious, major and numerous policy issues that have created a huge headache for America and her allies, on a scale never before seen.  I think they'd be irresponsible *not* to criticize bad policy.  Under Bush Sr. and Clinton, US foreign policy and the US military had a huge measure of respect for what they did.  Clinton gave the US military an incredibly good name with intervention in Bosnia, Kosovo and Croatia, all successful police actions with broad, near global international consensus.  <br>
<br>
Bush Sr. went to war for the right reasons, to defend a sovreign state, and brought an <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Arab Coalition</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> of armies along with him, keeping the alliance with Israel as he did so.  That alone was a PHENOMENAL achievement- his son can't even create a serious international coalition for a much larger-scale war, the Bush administration has made America shoulder the whole burden and ignored its Allies' concerns.  Rather than accept a compromise of policy to achieve consensus they preferred to stick their heads in the sand and go it alone.  The result is uncontrollable violence (even the Green Zone in Baghdad isn't entirely safe) and an appointed government so bereft of legitimacy or popular support that the new government has to meet in a guarded military compound.<br>
<br>
Three Presidents, one Democrat and two Republicans created sustainable policies and managed conflicts carefully, almost always achieving their goals and successfully accomplishing exit strategies.  This isn't about political ideology Dae, it's not about liberal, conservative or independent.  It's simply good policy, and bad policy.  I liked Bush Sr. a lot more than I liked Clinton as a president, his policies were superb, and he didn't seek popularity or fame like Clinton did.  GW Bush however, has endangered us all with his irresponsible and logically corrupt faith-based policies.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>i'll admit, abu ghraib(however the hell you spell it) isn't good. stuff was done there that should not have been done (most likely). <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
Most likely?  You wouldn't accept the photographs or the trial of Spc. Jeremy Sivits as proof then...why's that?<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>yet no one mentions the good things the us troops are doing<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
The vast majority of the good things you are talking about are legally required of the United States under international law.  The occupying authority is responsible for security, infrastructure, justice, government and every other natural responsibility of a sovreign government.  If it wasn't the legal responsibility of an occupying power to provide all these things, you can be sure the American taxpayer wouldn't be footing so large a bill, it's an unacceptable burden and not unforseen.  That's why (as reported in Bob Woodward's book) Colin Powell told the President before the war &quot;We will be owning another country, do you understand what that means?  We will be responsible for every aspect of life there and its betterment, you'll be President of two countries&quot;.  <br>
<br>
There is however, one major exception of occupation responsibility, and that is accountability, either locally, at the top, or internationally.  There is no means for US soldiers who commit crimes in Iraq to be held accountable to Iraqis.  It's also worth reiterating that no civilian administrator from the lowest to the highest level has been fired over any of the far-reaching policy catastrophes, that in itself, is truly staggering.<br>
  <br>
This also goes to the heart of why allies aren't providing significant numbers of troops or cash for post-war Iraq.  The same administration that insulted them and shut them out before the war, and pissed on the United Nations has now done a 180 when they're in trouble an in an election year- it smacks of expediency.  Allies can't reverse their position on the war by providing post-war support, it'd be a hegemonic policy conflict of staggering proportions and has placed them in a nearly impossible situation, both politically at home and diplomatically.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>in the end, when all is said and done, abu ghraib will most likely be a footnote in the history books<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
I doubt that very much.  People much like yourself said the same of the Mai Lai massacre and of the Amritsar massacre- but they have proved to be seminal moments in popular opposition to illegitimate occupation.  Iraqi children will learn about the horrors of Abu Ghraib under Saddam and under US occupation just as Vietnamese children today study the slaughter of innocents at My Lai, Irish children study Bloody Sunday and Indian children study Amritsar.  It's a sad, disgraceful and TOTALLY PREVENTABLE black mark on the history of a proud nation with fundamentally good values that much of the world looks to for leadership.  Reagan, Bush Sr. and Clinton provided that leadership, all GW Bush has provided is a denial he has made any mistakes.  Well here are <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.americanprogress.org/site/pp.asp?c=biJRJ8OVF&amp;b=64326" target="top">a hundred</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--> or so to choose from.<br>
<br>
 <p>Taranna Dhossarim<br>
65 Archon<br>
